  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Skillz Generation: Testing and Scaling Sports-based HIV Prevention</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The need for evidence-based HIV prevention services has never been more urgent. In 2008, nearly 40 percent of the 2.7 million HIV infections worldwide were among young people aged 15-24, and over one third of these were in southern Africa. 
Grassroot Soccer (GRS) seeks to reduce new HIV infections among over 30,000 underprivileged youth in townships and other disadvantaged communities in South Africa and Zimbabwe, using a soccer-themed curriculum called Generation Skillz, which aims to provide youth with the self-efficacy, knowledge and skills needed to protect themselves and others from HIV. GRS also aims to increase the uptake and demand for health services through HIV Counselling and Testing Tournaments, planning to test 4,000 people through the life of the project. 
Success in reversing the HIV epidemic depends not only on changing individuals&#x2019; attitudes, but also on changing the social norms fuelling the spread of HIV. While sport is perceived as having a great potential in addressing health, there is little rigorous proof that sport-based interventions can genuinely improve HIV and health-related behaviour. The Generation Skillz programme seeks not only to achieve improvements in HIV prevention, but also to prove their achievement through the most rigorous evaluation ever conducted in the field of sport-for-development.</narrative>
  </description>
